 visualization literacy: A feminist starting point -- t14. Is literacy what we need in an unequal data society? -- t15. Multimodal academic argument in data visualization -- tSection IV. Data visualization semiotics and aesthetics -- t16. What we talk about when we talk about beautiful data visualizations -- t17. A multimodal perspective on data visualization -- t18. Exploring narrativity in data visualization in journalism -- t19. The data epic : Visualization practices for narrating life and death at a distance -- t20. What a line can say : Investigating the semiotic potential of the connecting line in data visualizations -- t21. Humanizing data through 'data comics' : An introduction to graphic medicine and graphic social science -- tSection V. Data visualization and inequalities -- t22. Visualizing diversity: Data deficiencies and semiotic strategies -- t23. What is at stake in data visualization? A feminist critique of the rhetorical power of data visualizations in the media -- t24. The power of visualization choices: Different images of patterns in space -- t25. Making visible politically masked risks : Inspecting unconventional data visualization of the Southeast Asian haze -- t26. How interactive maps mobilize people in geoactivism -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aToday we are witnessing an increased use of data visualization in society. Across domains such as work, education and the news, various forms of graphs, charts and maps are used to explain, convince and tell stories. In an era in which more and more data are produced and circulated digitally, and digital tools make visualization production increasingly accessible, it is important to study the conditions under which such visual texts are generated, disseminated and thought to be of societal benefit. This book is a contribution to the multi-disciplined and multi-faceted conversation concerning the forms, uses and roles of data visualization in society. Do data visualizations do 'good' or 'bad'? Do they promote understanding and engagement, or do they do ideological work, privileging certain views of the world over others? The contributions in the book engage with these core questions from a range of disciplinary perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aCOMPUTERS / Data Visualization.2bisacsh  adata visualization, meaning-making, literacy, politics.1 aAiello, Giorgia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlamalhodaei, Aria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlberda, Alexandra P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArcher, Arlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhargava, Rahul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirchall, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinch, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCairo, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Pedro M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD'Ignazio, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngebretsen, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngebretsen, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEngelhardt, Yuri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEs, Karin v